review_blob: Pleasant with solid toasted malt backbone and mildly crisp drinkability. A bit nutty and mildly sweet, solid vienna, not as watery as many.

Draft. In the land of great IPAs this one stands out, its an extremely bright, refreshing and balanced example. Citrusy and tropical, slightly resiny, nice burst of floral and citrus in the nose. Dry and crisp at the end without overly bitter notes. Very, very good.

Aroma is a bit muted because this stuff is so thick its really hard to even coax a head out of it. Seriously dark, rich. The taste is nicely bitter and not cloying. The smokiness is more peaty and less sausage-y, which I like. Overall very pleasant, creamy and substantial pour.
beer_name: Flying Dog Brewhouse Rarities: Smoked Belgian Stout

review_blob: On tap @ Ed Smith Stadium. A fine IPA, which is to be expected these days in the US. Good hopping with citrus and mild tropical, solid malt backbone. Did not suck even as it warmed in the FL sun during the game. A brutal $8.50 for 16oz at the park, but well worth the extra 50 cents over an $8 bud.

Picked up a six of this in cans at Trader Joes in St Pete and very glad I did. I liked this beer a lot as it worked in many ways. Light enough to be an easy drinker on the beach without being wimpy. Spicy enough to hold its own with some thai food. And just really well balanced with wheat, orange and spice. If it had just a tang of lemon tartness Id call it perfect.
beer_name: Cigar City Florida Cracker White Ale

review_blob: Works pretty well, the bourbon notes temper and play off the strong, bitter hopping giving the base beer some more dimension. The finish is a bit confused so its not perfectly integrated. Still, a good quaff.

Nice, not over the top like many IPAs but complex in that you get tropical and citrus and pine and resin, fairly light and refreshing, more mellow on the finish than most IPAs, going more towards a british than an american in that sense.
Bottle. Thick, rich, black, bourbon nose, anise and bourbon, raisin, srong iced coffee. Yummy, not crazy complex but very yummy.
Very nice beer here, lots of tropical flavor extracted from the hops while keeping firmly in the pale ale domain. Refreshing and complex, well balanced.
beer_name: Sierra Nevada Beer Camp Tropical IPA

beer_brewer_name: Coney Island Brewing Company (Boston Beer Company)
review_blob: Pretty much undrinkable for me. Very happy to be splitting a bottle 3 ways. Pumpkin and coffee, just not a good combo.
beer_name: Coney Island Freaktoberfest: Big ol Pumpkin Ale (2015-)

review_blob: Very well done although almost pushing the limit of the category given the fruit involved. Big tropical hit of fruits on the melon and citrus side, not banana or coconut. Really comes through in the nose and almost juicy while also maintaining a soft body. Yummy.
beer_name: Boulevard Collaboration No. 5 Tropical Pale Ale

review_blob: Light coffee and malt. I love coffee milk and was hoping this might transport me back to my RI memories. Not quite, but its a solid beer. Perhaps a bit thin but hits the sweet stout target. Nicely. Drinkable, fairly smooth and a nice full pint can. Even better as it warms slightly and lets more coffee Come through.
bottle, not bad really, fairly clean with some light breadiness, a touch of grass and a bit of corn sweetness. Quaffable.
Lighter bodied than most oyster stouts Ive had, more like a big porter but the nice stoney minerality comes through, very pleasant.

Lovely beer, aged for a couple of years. Just a faint hint of smoke but the bourbon barrel comes through pretty big with vanilla and coconut. Raisins come through with some spice and solid malt, a nice dubbel.

Drinkable for for Ballast Point I expected something better. Seems lost in style, not quite a pale ale and i dont think really much like a Kolsch. Something too biscuity and lacking the crisp drinkability.

Im not really won over by these coffee IPAs coming out. Its two great tastes that, for me, dont necessarily taste great together. Having said that, this is a well made beer, aggressive hopping by FF comes right into play up front and then the coffee mingles with it and then trails off with more coffee notes. Its good but perhaps not exactly my cup of joe.
Falls short of pecan pie in a bottle but still quite good. Sort of a nut brown porter. Fairly rich but not hiding the alcohol completely. Porter roast comes through and mild coffee notes. Good.
beer_name: Clown Shoes Coffee Pecan Pie Porter

review_blob: I really like the inviting coffee aroma and the overall balance of this beer. Its a really well-constructed brew that brings a harmony to the ingredients. A sophisticated quaff.

Solid, lots of wheat in the nose, a bit bready, and it continues in the taste, adding a bit of orange and little bit of refreshing spiciness. For the relatively low abv it had a good amount of body and flavor. Wheat character wa a bit more towards hefe than most wits.

beer_brewer_name: Magic Hat Brewing Company (North American Breweries)
review_blob: Surprised by the fairly high ratings I see. Perhaps I got a bad bottle. The aroma was very promising, dark chocolate, roasted nuts and vanilla bean. But it all fell apart, the head receded to a film, and in the mouth it was quite thin and a bit harsh, especially until it warmed up. The flavors did not mingle but rather stood by themselves. Drinkable but a let down.
Very pleasant quaff, Soft, lighter on the palate than you would expect but still full bodied and warming. Will pair well with a multi-course meal with various dishes.
Draft. A solid offering. Nice, foamy then filmy head. Resiny, a little pine, dry but not too bitter.
Draft. Quite good, the dunkel aspects shine through with solid malting, some banana and bazooka. The spicing is subtle enough to make this very drinkable and the ABV is warming, not hot. Good stuff.
beer_name: Neshaminy Creek Punkless Dunkel Pumpkin Wheat Ale

review_blob: Despite the vanilla and creaminess, which works as funnel cake, this is not just a one and done beer, its a drinkable ale because the sweetness is not overdone, and the breadiness is not too heavy. Instead it sort of surprises and keeps things interesting. Something comes off just subtly harsh, bit its not a big deal. I like this more from the can than the nitro, where it is more creamy and more like funnel cake, good as a novelty but less overly drinkable.
An OK IPA, decent but not huge hop presence, slightly resiny, just sort of felt a bit heavy.

I am loving these great session IPAs in the vein of Stones groundbreaking GoTo. Solid citrus and fruit in the nose and tase, dry bite, not bitter, not thin. Good stuff. I do wonder about naming conflicts with Harpoons beer of the same name.

Hopefully the name will be updated soo by the admins, Im an idiot and didnt fill it in correctly. Until then, the proper name is "Forgotten Boardwalk Attraction No 1 - Twisted Mister". This is the first of their special offering series, packaged with their usual creative labeling in a corked, 375ml bottle. And I do mean corked, I needed a corkscrew to get the darn thing out.

Anyway, this beer is as close to a home run as Ive had from this new-ish brewery. They have a solid smoked porter and a decent IPA but what I like is their willingness to experiment. This beer has a really wild lime and hop citrus nose, and it persists. Good looking beer with a decent but not overwhelming head. It doesnt waste its 8%, its mouth filling and warming and strange, with the gin barrels (I guess) adding a really interesting and pleasant character. Its good from start to finish, not 100% perfectly integrated, but really good.

The brewer Dave is really pushing the edges with some fruit experiments, at the brewery recently I had a mango infused saison. Very good (not as good as this), interesting and drinkable. Again, not 100% perfectly integrated, but these beers are really showing promise.
beer_name: Forgotten Boardwalk Attraction No. 1 - Twisted Mister

review_blob: Solid IPA, which is pretty much a requirement for any American IPA at this point. If it isnt really good it really shouldnt be produced. What is nice about that fact is it makes it easy to support the hyper-local brewing scenes which are becoming ubiquitous in populated areas. Enjoy your locally made beer, its part of where you live!
2015 - Draft at Monks. This was excellent. slightly hazy pink with mild effervescence shooting raspberry essence into your head. Wonderful balance of fresh fruit, tartness, and malt.
beer_name: Russian River Framboise for a Cure (2013-)

review_blob: Underrated I think. This has great toasted and biscuit character while being very drinkable, not thin, and with an excellent dry bite. Well done. I declare this be the beer that defines a craft "Vienna"

Im a sucker for harvest or wet hop ales, I mean they are just declicious in general and this one is certainly right on. Big, resiny, fresh, all over the fruit spectrum. And it nicely cleansed my palate after a bunch of smoky foods and smoky beers.
Very good, light smoke integrates well with the base marzen and the beer is well balanced. Clean and quaffable.
First TH brew, finally. Very enjoyable, clean, interesting, smokiness a bit different from the german beechwood, given the house-smoking, and it works nicely.

Draft. This was excellent. The Apple Brandy character was strong and appreciated, offering uncommon barrel flavors that worked perfectly with the beer. Rich and satisfying, smoky and slightly sweet, very drinkable.
beer_name: Captain Lawrence Smoke from the Oak (Apple Brandy Barrel)

review_blob: Brooklyn knows how to make silky smooth porter/stouts with strong but balanced flavors. No exception here, great, rich, base porter and good, classic german smoke flavor. Could even amp up the smoke a notch.
Floral nose. It is tart, especially up front, lots of fruit. Gives way to wheat character. A bit less spicy or funky than I look for in saison but refreshing and good nonetheless.

Smells and looks like root beer. Tastes like root beer. Leaves an aftertaste that reminds you its not root beer. I think you should just drink root beer if you want a root beer. There are better ways of consuming alcohol without wanting to know you are doing so, but frats will undoubtedly love this.
beer_name: Small Town Not Your Fathers Root Beer (5.9%)

review_blob: Amazingly, this didnt suck at all. It was really pretty refreshing and at 2.5 just enough to take an edge off.
Bottle at brewery. Pretty good porter, has a sort of house quality with overtones of the stout. Nice looking with a sturdy head. Light roast and cocoa. Finishes slightly thin with a slight sourness.

Nitro Tap at brewhouse near glasnevin. For me, this beer is underrated, I found it excellent. Nuanced, creamy, rich and satisfying. Stood up to a [great] smoky burger at the brewpub. Nice dry stout and worth a short break from drinking Guinness.
UPDATED: APR 19, 2016
Very solid Russian imp stout, thick rich and creamy with basically everything you want and nothing you dont. Strong showing at the brewery, 5 for 5 with the beers I tried.
Good refreshing beer with nice cranberry tang. Could be even a tad less sweet

Very solid sour, well balanced and a pronounced dry sour quenching beer.
At the brewery fresh and appealing with decent head and lacing.
Decent alt, too light in color but if you closed your eyes the taste is pretty well on style. Good malting and nice, drying finish.
Very nice, crisp, fresh and refreshing. Nice sourness without being overtly tart. Love to see more people making these flavorful low ABV beers. More Berliners and Gose beers please!
Solid IPA, the color is nice, muddy red, not sure if Id know there was anything different with my eyes closed. Perhaps a bit more malt on the finish.
beer_name: Captain Lawrence Pilot Batch #116 Red IPA

review_blob: Excellent beer. The deScription is spot on, this is right there between schwarzbier and smoked porter. The smokiness is so well done it melds with , doesnt dominate the somewhat creamy sweet, light coffee malt character. The lagering keeps it clean and sharp at the finish. More please.
Totally quaffable summery beer. I like these hoppy wheat beers in general. This one is well balanced but perhaps a tad bland. Still pleasant and certainly a crowd pleaser.
